Solution 3.6. It is easy to show by example that $\sum_{\mu} D^{\mu \mu}$ is not invariant. Let $D^{0x} = 1$ and all other components be zero. For a boost in the $x$ -direction $D^{0'0'} = - eta \gamma$ , $D^{x'x'} = - eta \gamma$ so that $\sum_{\mu} D^{\mu \mu} = 0$ but $\sum_{\mu'} D^{\mu' \mu'} = -2 eta \gamma$ . The proof for $\sum_{\mu} D_{\mu \mu}$ is similar.
For a Lorentz transformation $\Lambda_{
u}^{\mu '}$ , we know $\mathsf{D}_{\mu '}^{
u '} = \Lambda_{\mu '}^{\alpha}\Lambda_{ eta}^{
u '} \mathsf{D}_{\alpha}^{ eta}$ so that
$$
\sum_{\mu^{'}} \mathrm {D}_{\mu^{'}}^{\mu^{'}} = \sum_{\mu^{'}} \Lambda_{\mu^{'}}^{\alpha} \Lambda_{ eta}^{\mu^{'}} \mathrm {D}_{ eta}^{\alpha} = \delta_{ eta}^{\alpha} \mathrm {D}_{\alpha}^{ eta} = \sum_{\mu} \mathrm {D}_{\mu}^{\mu},
$$
and hence this summation is invariant.
